A plea agreement was revealed with one of Michael Vick's co-defendants in a federal dogfighting conspiracy case, potentially complicating Vick's legal battle.
Tony Taylor, one of the organizers of dogfights across state lines, changed his plea to guilty and implicated Vick in bankrolling the scheme.
Vick, facing charges and protests, maintained his innocence and vowed to clear his name.
The indictment detailed gruesome practices in the dogfighting ring, leading to public outrage.
Despite the legal turmoil, Vick's lawyer expressed confidence in proving his innocence.
The plea deal signaled a significant development in the case, with potential implications for Vick's future.
